## Scope correction

- [well-established] RDF 1.1 reification, N3 formulae, and RDF 1.2 triple terms all permit statements about statements; therefore reification is not an expressivity wall.
- [well-established] RDF 1.2 triple terms denote propositions, may remain unasserted, and are normally connected to an ordinary resource through `rdf:reifies`; that resource can then be typed as a belief, claim, norm, commitment, etc. [RDF 1.2 Concepts](https://www.w3.org/TR/rdf12-concepts/#section-triple-terms).
- [well-established] RDF 1.2 is currently a Candidate Recommendation rather than a completed W3C Recommendation. [RDF 1.2 Semantics](https://www.w3.org/TR/rdf12-semantics/).
- [well-established] N3 `{ … }` formulae provide quoted graph-valued content with variables and quantification. [W3C N3 submission](https://www.w3.org/TeamSubmission/n3/#Formulae).
- [well-established] Bare RDF supplies the carrier, not UFO’s temporal, intentional, causal, or deontic consequence relation; RDF explicitly anticipates separately defined semantic extensions and entailment regimes. [RDF 1.2 Semantics](https://www.w3.org/TR/rdf12-semantics/#semantic-extensions-and-entailment-regimes).

Notation below uses `:r rdf:reifies <<( :s :p :o )>>`; the quoted triple is not asserted unless `:s :p :o` is also present.

## Per-construct audit

| Family | Construct | Concrete carrier | Rules or semantic qualification | Verdict |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| UFO-B | Event / Perdurant | `:e a ufo:Event; ufo:begin :t1; ufo:end :t2.` | Interval ordering and event typing fit OWL/RDF datatypes plus safe rules. | [well-established] Expressible. |
| UFO-B | Participation | `:p a ufo:Participation; ufo:participant :alice; ufo:event :e; ufo:participantRole :buyer.` | Use the participation node when role, interval, disposition, or manifestation must be attached; Horn rules can project `participant(:e,:alice)`. | [well-established] Expressible as an n-ary relation through ordinary node reification. |
| UFO-B | Temporal parts | `:e1 ufo:temporalPartOf :e; ufo:during :i1.` | `part(x,z) ← part(x,y), part(y,z)` and interval-containment rules are function-free Datalog. | [well-established] Expressible; finite safe Datalog remains decidable and implementable. |
| UFO-B | Event mereology | `:e ufo:hasEventPart :e1,:e2; ufo:atomic false.` | Transitivity, overlap, proper-part and fusion checks need rules/constraints; unrestricted “a fusion exists for every condition” needs existential rules or generated identifiers. | [plausible] Operational UFO mereology is decidable in guarded existential Datalog±; unrestricted classical mereology pushes toward FOL and loses general decidability. |
| UFO-B | Causation | `:c a ufo:CausalRelation; ufo:cause :e1; ufo:effect :e2; ufo:underSituation :S.` | Do not make causation transitive by default; domain-specific causal rules can inspect event, time and situation nodes. Counterfactual causation requires explicit worlds plus a counterfactual semantics. | [plausible] Structural causation is straightforward; full counterfactual causation needs a modal rule extension. |
| UFO-B | Situations / world-states | `:S a ufo:Situation; ufo:includes :r1. :r1 rdf:reifies <<( :door :state :open )>>.` Alternatively, use an N3 formula or named graph. | Named-graph names are only syntactically paired with graphs, so an application axiom must define “graph `g` is the content of situation `S`.” [RDF 1.2 Concepts](https://www.w3.org/TR/rdf12-concepts/#section-dataset). | [well-established] Expressible as quoted-triple sets; satisfaction and possible-world accessibility require a semantic extension. |
| UFO-C | Agent | `:a a ufo:Agent, ufo:PhysicalAgent.` | OWL/RDFS handles taxonomy; rules can derive agency only from explicitly adopted criteria. | [well-established] Expressible. |
| UFO-C | Physical / social Object | `:car a ufo:PhysicalObject. :currency a ufo:SocialObject; ufo:recognizedBy :community.` | Recognition, creation by communicative acts, and dependence on a community require explicit relations/rules. UFO-C distinguishes physical/social agents and objects this way. [UFO-C account](https://www.inf.ufes.br/~gguizzardi/UFO-S.pdf). | [well-established] Expressible. |
| UFO-C | Goal | `:g a ufo:Goal; ufo:content :F.` where `:F` contains/reifies the desired propositions. | A rule may define fulfillment from `satisfies(:S,:F)`; arbitrary Boolean/quantified content needs N3 formulae or an RDF formula AST. | [plausible] Expressible; fulfillment semantics is rule-defined. |
| UFO-C | Intention | `:i a ufo:Intention; ufo:inheresIn :a; ufo:goal :g.` | Rules can connect intention, planned action and satisfaction without asserting the goal content. UFO-C treats intentions as desired states the agent commits to pursue. [UFO-C account](https://www.inf.ufes.br/~gguizzardi/UFO-S.pdf). | [plausible] Expressible; causal efficacy of intentions is an adopted rule theory. |
| UFO-C | Belief | `:b a ufo:Belief; ufo:believer :a; rdf:reifies <<( :moon :orbits :earth )>>.` | The quoted proposition remains unasserted; belief closure, justification and contradiction policies require rules over reifiers/formulae. | [well-established] Expressible without confusing belief with truth. |
| UFO-C | Commitment | `:c a ufo:Commitment; ufo:debtor :a; ufo:creditor :b; ufo:content :F; ufo:status :open.` | Lifecycle rules derive active, fulfilled, violated or discharged states from events and situation satisfaction. | [well-established] Expressible; UFO-C explicitly models commitments as social moments paired with claims over one content. [UFO-C account](https://www.inf.ufes.br/~gguizzardi/UFO-S.pdf). |
| UFO-C | Claim | `:cl a ufo:Claim; ufo:claimant :b; ufo:against :a; ufo:content :F; ufo:counterpart :c.` | Equality/cardinality constraints can enforce one paired content; SHACL is appropriate for record completeness. | [well-established] Expressible. |
| UFO-C | Social roles | `:rr a ufo:RoleHolding; ufo:holder :a; ufo:roleType :Tenant; ufo:inContext :lease; ufo:during :i.` | Context-conditioned acquisition/loss is naturally handled by temporal rules; full anti-rigidity is modal and needs explicit worlds or a modal checker. | [plausible] Role holdings are decidably expressible; UFO’s modal anti-rigidity theorem is not supplied by RDF semantics. |
| UFO-C | Normative description | `:contract a ufo:NormativeDescription; ufo:recognizedBy :org; ufo:defines :n.` | This matches UFO-C’s treatment of contracts/directives as social objects defining norms and roles. [UFO-C specification](https://ontology.com.br/ufo/ufo-c/spec/ufo/ufo-c/package-summary). | [well-established] Expressible. |
| UFO-C | Norm | `:n a ufo:Norm; ufo:condition :F1; ufo:consequent :F2; ufo:modality ufo:Obligatory.` | Rules over quoted formulae can activate obligations and create commitments/claims; defeasible priorities or violation-by-absence require stratified negation or ASP. | [plausible] Positive norms fit safe Datalog; defeasible norms remain decidable on finite data under stratified Datalog/ASP, but are non-monotonic. |
| UFO-C | Delegation | `:d a ufo:Delegation; ufo:delegator :a; ufo:delegatee :b; ufo:content :F; ufo:foundingEvent :speechAct.` | A rule can transfer/create the corresponding intention or commitment/claim pair. Automatic creation of fresh nodes needs deterministic Skolem IRIs or guarded existential rules. | [plausible] Expressible and implementable; authority, revocation and redelegation must be supplied by the chosen normative ruleset. |

## Family verdict

- [well-established] **UFO-B: yes at the representation level.** Events, participation, temporal parts, mereology, causation and situations all have direct RDF node/reifier encodings.
- [plausible] **UFO-B’s ordinary executable fragment fits finite safe Datalog over explicit events, intervals and worlds**, giving decidable materialization; unrestricted fusion axioms or counterfactual causation require existential/FOL/modal extensions with weaker decidability.
- [well-established] **UFO-C: yes at the representation level.** RDF 1.2 reifiers and N3 formulae remove the alleged inability to represent propositional attitudes, commitments, claims and norms.
- [plausible] **A practical UFO-C consequence relation can use function-free stratified Datalog over quoted content**, with explicit world/context/time parameters; it is decidable on finite datasets and implementable in existing rule engines.
- [well-established] **Bare RDF 1.2 alone does not validate the full intended UFO semantics.** It does not natively make beliefs opaque, evaluate goals, create obligations, enforce role anti-rigidity, or interpret named graphs as worlds.
- [plausible] **Full fidelity to arbitrary quantified modal/deontic UFO axioms requires quantified modal/deontic FOL or an equivalent theorem-prover layer.** Such a layer is implementable, but validity is undecidable in general, so timeouts and incomplete proof search must be exposed.
- [well-established] Consequently, the corrected answer is **“all listed constructs are statable; many useful fragments are decidably rule-executable; unrestricted full-UFO semantics is not guaranteed decidable.”**

The earlier axis-1 claims in [expressivity-analysis.md](/home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/arch/expressivity-analysis.md:26), especially G7/G10, should therefore be narrowed from “not statable” to “not natively interpreted by RDF/OWL entailment.”